<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-13 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ceasefire Agreed Upon In Monrovia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Factions fighting in the Liberian
capital of Monrovia since a week ago have agreed upon a ceasefire
after US helicopters ferried more than 1,000 foreigners out of
the country, a report reaching here today said.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by Ghana's Deputy Foreign Minister Mohamed
Ibn Chambas late yesterday following negotiations which also
involved the United Nations, aid agencies and the high command of
the peacekeeping force ECOMOG, the report said.
</P>
<P>
"An immediate ceasefire has been agreed among the combatants,"
Chambas was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
According to Chambas, Liberia's ruling council had also agreed
that ECOMOG should cordon off the Barclay Training Center
barracks, the target of shelling since fighting broke out a week
ago when the government armed police tried to arrest Krahn
militia warlord General Roosevelt Johnson on murder charges.
</P>
<P>
Chambas said Johnson had agreed to cooperate fully in
implementing the new truce agreement.
</P>
<P>
The ceasefire agreement was seen as a result of the mediation
team sent on Thursday by Ghana's President Jerry Rawlings who
helped broker the peace accord signed last August in Nigeria. The
peace accord has been derailed by the renewed violence.
</P>
<P>
After a week's fighting, looting and anarchy has been
widespread in Monrovia, the report said.
</P>
<P>
"No one knows what is going to happen to the civilian
population. People (gunmen) are going around drunk or drugged.
It's a big jungle there," the report quoted Roland Waver,
spokesman for the International Committee of the Red Cross, as
saying in Geneva. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
