<HEADLINE> Iran, Libya Condemn Israeli Attacks on S. Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Akbar Hashemi
Rafsanjani and Libyan Leader Muammar al-Gaddafi today jointly
condemned Israeli attacks in south Lebanon during their
telephone conversation.
</P>
<P>
Iran's official news agency IRNA reported that Rafsanjani
attacked Israel's brutal and merciless killings of innocent
Lebanese civilians.
</P>
<P>
He severely criticized the international fora and countries,
which staunchly advocated so-called human rights, for maintaining
a continued silence towards the blatant aggression on Lebanon,
the report added.
</P>
<P>
Rafsanjani was quoted as saying that certain Islamic and
Arab states do not show sufficient interest in trying to find
a common strategy to challenge the aggressive policies of the
occupying Israeli regime.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the need for a joint action by the Islamic
states to defend the rights of the suppressed people of
Lebanon and Palestine and deal effectively with the Israeli
adventurism.
</P>
<P>
Gaddafi said in a telephone call that the recent Israeli
aggression is based on state terrorism supported by the
U.S. in the region and that the practice of state terrorism
by the Zionists recognizes neither borders nor limitations.
</P>
<P>
The Libyan leader was quoted as saying that the silence of the
international fora and community, the indifference of the regional
 states are the outcome of Sharm El-Sheikh summit held last month
in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Gaddafi hoped that the Islamic states need to adopt a firm and
independent policy in line with Islam alongside Iran. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
