<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Israel Continues Aggressions against South Lebanon (Part II) (by Shao Jie) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hariri and Boueiz left Beirut after they had their second
meeting in a few hours with President Elias Hrawi. House Speaker
Nabih Berri attended the first meeting in the Beirut presidential
Palace this morning.
</P>
<P>
Before the second meeting in the Presidential Palace, the
foreign minister announced that he had made contact with Lebanese
representative in the United Nations, Samir Mubarak, on lodging a
complaint with the Security Council against the Israeli agressions.
</P>
<P>
He said he had also held contact with Lebanese representative
in the Arab league, Hisham Damashqia, and instructed him to ask an
urgent session of the Arab League in order to put an end to the
Israeli agressions against Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Boueiz said that contacts with Lebanese envoys to other
countries were being intensively conducted.
</P>
<P>
He added that he would call meetings today and Sunday of
diplomatic envoys of the five permanent member states of the
U.N. Security Council, member states of the European Union and the
Arab League and other countries in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
He said that he had also held contacts with French Foreign
Minister Herve De Charette and Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa, and briefed them the real situation in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Boueiz announced earlier, after the first meeting with
Lebanon's three top leaders, that his country had decided to lodge
a complaint with the U.N. Security Council against Israel's
continuous agressions.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon made the decision when Israel was continuing air raids
and bombardments at southern Lebanese villages .
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said he believes that the United States
would use its "veto" right on holding a meeting of the Security
Council, or on any resolution the council could adopt.
</P>
<P>
"But we should hold the Security Council its responsibility,
and We will never accept a current logic that the (Israeli)
agressions contribute to consolidating the peace process," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"There is no justifications at all for the Israeli attacks at
Lebanon and its agressions against Lebanon's territories and
people," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said that contacts and coordinations were "continuing with
a number of countries in a purpose to put an end to the Israeli
agressions, and to prevent any (Israeli) candidate from
benefiting from these mistakes in the (upcoming Israeli)
elections." 
</P>
</TEXT>
