<HEADLINE> Ramaphosa To Help Black Business Drive: Mandela </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Constitutional Assembly
Chairman Cyril Ramaphosa was the best man to spearhead a
government endorsed drive aimed at black business empowerment,
President Nelson Mandela said today.
</P>
<P>
Mandela made the remarks at his official Cape Town residence
after the announcement that Ramaphosa would soon quit parliament
and take up a position as senior executive in the private sector.
</P>
<P>
Ramaphosa, a former trade unionist, would reportedly join top
black entrepreneur Dr. Nthato Motlana's New Africa Investment
Ltd. (NAIL).
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters at a press conference, Mandela said the
government wanted to ensure that the wide gap between white and
black business was closed.
</P>
<P>
Mandela said big business was by definition white, while
blacks, including colored and Indians, were confined to small
and medium-sized business.
</P>
<P>
"We want the economy to be improved and it cannot be improved
if this wide gap still exists," said the president.
</P>
<P>
To this end, no one was better qualified to achieve this than
Ramaphosa, who is also Secretary-general of the African National
Congress, he added.
</P>
<P>
However, Mandela said Ramaphosa's new position within the
NAIL, though to be announced soon, would only come into effect
once the final constitution was finalized.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Ramaphosa, said he had chosen NAIL because it was
one of the largest black companies involved in strategic
investments and which would use this to assist with black
empowerment.
</P>
<P>
"NAIL is well placed to assist people like myself to assist
in the role we'd like to play," said Ramaphosa.
</P>
<P>
Motlana, who was also present when Mandela made the
announcement, said although blacks had "won the political
battle, real power is economic."
</P>
<P>
"We need to mobilize young men as able as Cyril Ramaphosa, who
can help to economically empower black people" said Motlana.
</P>
<P>
NAIL and the National Union of Mineworkers are part of a black
consortium who are attempting to buy out Johannesburg
Consolidated Investment subsidiary JOHNNIC.
</P>
<P>
JOHNNIC is the parent company of Times Media Limited which
owns publications like the Financial Mail and Business Day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
