<HEADLINE> S. African Constitutional Assembly Chairmman To Quit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Constitutional Assembly
Chairman Cyril Ramaphosa will resign from Parliament once the
South Africa's final constitution is completed. He plans to serve
as senior executive in the private sector.
</P>
<P>
This was made public today by President Nelson Mandela who was
speaking to reporters at his official Cape Town residence.
</P>
<P>
Mandela said that former trade unionist Ramaphosa would soon
quit parliament and join top black entrepreneur Dr. Nthato
Motlana's New Africa Investment Ltd (NAIL).
</P>
<P>
However, Comrade Ramaphosa would remain Secretary-general of
the African National Congress (ANC) and a member of the party's
National Executive Committee, said the president.
</P>
<P>
Mandela, flanked by Motlana and Ramaphosa, told reporters
Ramaphosa's presence in the private sector would further cement
the critical partnership between the ANC and government on one
hand, and business, trade unions and civil society on the other.
</P>
<P>
In a statement on the future of Ramaphosa, the president spoke
highly of Ramaphosa's contribution to the ANC, the
nation-building effort and task of reconstruction and
development.
</P>
<P>
Comrade Ramaphosa had done sterling work during the difficult
process of writing the interim and final constitution, said the
statement, adding he was an asset both to the ANC and the nation
as a whole. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
