<HEADLINE> Xinhua International News Summary at 1630 GMT on April 13 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Fighting and bad weather in Chechnya blocked face to
face talks between Moscow's peace envoy and Chechen separatist
leader Dzhokhar Dudayev, Itar-Tass news agency reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- Afghan government troops launched a major
offensive in Western Afghanistan in a bid to retake the strategic
city of Herat from the Taliban Islamic student militia, a report
from Kabul said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
MOGADISHU -- At least eight people were killed and 27 others
were wounded when clashes erupted between the militiamen of
General Mohamed Farah Aidid and those of the Rahanwein Resistance
Army (RRA) at Bur Jebbo and Gof Gudud villages on Friday.
</P>
<P>
DAMASCUS -- The Syrian-Lebanese summit meeting which was
scheduled to take place in Damascus Saturday was postponed to an
unidentified date due to the escalation of the Israeli military
campaign against Lebanese villages and towns, diplomatic sources
said.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Four children were killed and six others wounded in
Israeli air raid which began around 2:00 p.m. local time (11:00
GMT) Saturday at an ambulance rolling on the Hanniyeh road near
the port city of Sour in Lebanon. Meanwhile, the pro-Iranian
Hezbollah, or Party of God, announced that its guerrilla hit an
Israeli military helicopter with a Sam7 anti-air missile when it
was carrying out an air raid at the southern Lebanese village of
As-Smaiyeh in Sour.
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- Thirty people were feared killed when a 54-seat
bus fell into a river after hitting rails near Rajahmundry in
Andhra Pradesh, India, in the early hours Saturday, the Press
Trust of India said.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Israel has imposed a blockade upon the Beirut Port
since early Saturday morning and prevented any ship from entering
the port.
</P>
<P>
PYONGYANG -- The Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK)
insists on signing a peace treaty to replace the armistice
agreement signed at the end of the Korean War in 1953, a DPRK
foreign ministry spokesman said Friday.
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI -- Twenty people were killed in two separate road
accidents in Western Kenya on Friday. Ten people belonging to one
family were killed in Kisii District when they were on their way
to collect a body of another dead relative. Another ten perished
in a smash-up in Kakamega involving a lorry and a Peugeot 504.
</P>
</TEXT>
