<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-13 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Donors' Conference on Bosnia Ends with $1.23 Billion Pledged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The Second Donors' Conference
for the reconstruction of Bosnia ended today in Brussels with 1.23
billion U.S. dollars in new commitments for 1996 pledged by
representatives from 55 countries and 29 international
organizations.
</P>
<P>
An earlier meeting in December 1995 raised 600 million dollars
in pledges for reconstruction, bringing the total funds available
from the international community to more than 1.8 billion dollars
for this year alone out of a planned four-year reconstruction
program of 5.1 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The two-day conference, co-hosted by the European Commission and
the World Bank, was chaired by European Commissioner Hans van den
Broek and World Bank President James K. Wolfensohn.
</P>
<P>
Van den Broek announced new commitments of 260 million dollars
for the remainder of 1996 from the European Union (EU) budget.
</P>
<P>
For the longer term up to 1999, he foresaw an overall
contribution to the region from the EU budget alone totalling some
1.3 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
For the World Bank, Wolfensohn announced that, in addition to
the 150 million dollars pledged at the December meeting, a further
160 million dollars in new commitments from the International
Development Association is envisaged during the remainder of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The Bosnian government was represented at the meeting by Prime
Minister Hasan Muratovic for Bosnia and Herzegovina, and by Prime
Minister Izudin Kapetanovic for the Muslim-Croat Federation. The
Serbs declined to attend after being refused separate
representation.
</P>
<P>
It was announced at the meeting that a comprehensive mid-term
review of the peace process under the auspices of the Peace
Implementation Conference will take place in Florence, Italy in
mid June.
</P>
<P>
Representatives also agreed to meet again after Bosnian
elections this autumn to review the progress of aid to the region
and to address future reconstruction needs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
