<HEADLINE> Clinton Calls for Law Priority in Fighting Terrorism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 13 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
said here today that it must be a top law enforcement priority for
the United States to fight against terrorism.
</P>
<P>
In a radio message tape recorded Friday, Clinton warned that
terrorism had entered a technologically sophisticated "new era"
with open borders and simple means of travel.
</P>
<P>
He said that he wants anti-terrorism legislation that stops
terrorist groups from raising money in the United States, as well
as deportation laws for foreigners connected with terrorist
activities.
</P>
<P>
The president made the statement just a few days before the
one-year anniversary of the April 19 explosion that left 158 dead
in Oklahoma City.
</P>
<P>
He blamed House Republicans for stalling his proposed
anti-terrorism bill under pressure from the gun lobby.
</P>
<P>
"Under pressure from the Washington gun lobby, House
Republicans took that bill apart, piece by piece," Clinton said,
adding that "it's time to put it back together." 
</P>
</TEXT>
