<HEADLINE> Barak Plays Down Significance of Diplomatic Initiatives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Foreign Minister Ehud Barak
stated today that Israel does not attach great significance to
diplomatic activities at this stage of the Lebanese war, reported
Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
"Now that our guns and aircraft are hitting Hezbollah, I
believe that time will come for diplomatic contacts only when the
government in Beirut realizes its responsibility to take over
Hezbollah," said Barak, the former chief of general staff who
directed the 1993 Operation Accountability in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
However, Barak will leave for Washington Monday for talks with
top American officials and, possibly, other officials from the
Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Barak told the radio that he had already had contacts with
European foreign ministers, U.S. Secretary of State Warren
Christopher and his counterparts of the Israel's neighboring
states.
</P>
<P>
"Basically, it is an exchange of information about what is
going on," he said.
</P>
<P>
He denied pressure from the international community for halting
attacks.
</P>
<P>
Barak, widely regarded as a hawk in the Labor Party, said that
every effort had been made to avoid hurting civilian populations
in Lebanon, but Israel cannot fully guarantee that no civilians
are victimized. He holds the Lebanese government responsible for
any civilian casualties.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli foreign minister said that it would be "quite good"
if Israel keeps tranquility in the north for more than two years
up till 1999 by relentlessly countering Hezbollah this
time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
