<HEADLINE> Chechen Parliament Names New Premier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 13 (Xinhua) -- A Russian general was today
appointed as Chechnya's new prime minister by the Moscow-backed
Chechen government, reports reaching Moscow said.
</P>
<P>
The appointment of Lieutenant-General Nikolai Koshman is aimed
at strengthening the executive power of the republic and takes
account of the multi-national composition of the republic's
population, said the Chechen republic's leader and former prime
minister Doku Zavgayev.
</P>
<P>
Before Koshman's appointment, the Moscow-backed Chechen
government consisted only of ethnic Chechens.
</P>
<P>
Koshman was formerly deputy head of Russia's Railway Troops and
an adviser to Oleg Lobov, the Russian presidential envoy in
Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
Zavgayev won controversial elections in Chechnya last December
which were boycotted by separatists loyal to rebel leader Dzhokhar
Dudayev. 
</P>
</TEXT>
