<DOCNO> XIE19960413.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-13 15:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Keeps Winning Streak in Swimming Asians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Chinese swimmers continued their
triumphant march in the Fifth Asian Swimming Championships
Saturday with seven more gold medals to their credit here.
</P>
<P>
China now leads the field with 11 golds, six silvers and two
bronzes on the medal tally.
</P>
<P>
Japan, adding two more golds Saturday, followed with six golds,
8 silvers and 5 bronzes while South Korea placed third with one
silver and 6 bronzes.
</P>
<P>
Zhao Lifeng opened the day's swimming finals by winning the
men's 100 meters freestyle with a fastest time of 51.78 seconds,
followed by Japanese Shunsuke Ito, winner of the 200 meters
freestyle Friday, in 51.84 and Uzbekistan's Kabanov Vyacheslav in
51.99.
</P>
<P>
But Zhao's time was 0.27 seconds short of the Asian mark of
50.51 seconds set by retired Chinese Shen Jianqiang in 1989.
</P>
<P>
China's national champion Shan Ying took the women's 100 meters
freestyle in 55.95 seconds, far from the Asian standard set in
1994 by her teammate Le Jingyi.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Suzu Chiba and South Korea's Lee Bo-Eun were second
and third places, in 56.71 and 57.69 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Zeng Qiliang won the Chinese swimming team's third gold
Saturday as he returned a fastest time of one minute 2.88 seconds
in the men's 100 meters breaststroke, beating Japan's Asian record
holder Arira Hayashi by 11 hundredths of a second. Hayashi's
two-year-old Asian mark is 1:01.76.
</P>
<P>
Another Japanese Yoshinobu Miyazaki was timed at 1:03.28 for
the bronze medal.
</P>
<P>
Han Xue of China set a new Asian championships record of
1:10.07 on the route to winning the women's 100 meters
breaststroke. Her time is 1.46 seconds slower than the Asian
record held by another Chinese Dai Guohong in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Masami Tanaka and Kyoko Iwasaki took the silver and
bronze medals in 1:10.34 and 1:12.01.
</P>
<P>
Japanese finished one-two in the men's 400 meters individual
medley final as Tatsuya Kinugasa and Toshiaki Kurasawa were timed
4:26.29 and 4:28.81. Both were far short of the Asian record of
4:20.03 set by Thai Ratapong Sirisanont two years ago.
</P>
<P>
South Korea's Kim Bang-Hyun was third in 4:30.35.
</P>
<P>
Wu Yanyan of China set a new championships record of 4:46.48 in
the women's 400 individual medley. Japanese Fumie Kurotori and
China's Chen Yan finished second and third.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese team won the men's 4x200 meters freestyle relay in
7:36.77, beating Uzbekstan and South Korea into second and third
places.
</P>
<P>
Chinese divers swept the two events, with Lao Jiezhen winning
the women's platform title and Fan Huaqiang taking the men's three
meters springboard. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
