<HEADLINE> Filipinos Start to Construct Subic Techno-Park </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines today started to
construct the Subic Techno-Park (STEP) with President Fidel Ramos
attending the groundbreaking ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The 50-hectare industrial estate is a joint project of the
Subic Bay Metropolitan Authority (SBMA), Japan International
Development Organization (JAIDO) and Bank of Tokyo with an
investment of 22 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, the president described the venture as "another
bold step toward 'Philippines 2000'."
</P>
<P>
According to Ramos, approximately 50 supporting industry
companies will set up facilities in the Subic Bay and generate
about 10,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
The STEP is intended for the country's small and medium
enterprises (SMES). The promotion of SMES in Subic will in turn
encourage the development of supporting industries in the
Philippines through technology transfer, the president said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his appreciation to the Japanese investors for
choosing the Philippines in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
The development of the industrial estate further boosts the
freeport's bid to become a major investment destination in the
Asia-Pacific region, Ramos said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
