<HEADLINE> More Air Traffic For Inland Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Air traffic has grown rapidly in
the southwest province of Guizhou in recent years, with 26 routes
now opened between this provincial capital and other Chinese
cities and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The Guiyang airport receives over 30 regular and charter
flights and handles about 2,500 passengers each day.
</P>
<P>
Located in China's hinterland, Guizhou used to have only a few
air connections with some other inland cities.
</P>
<P>
Since 1990 the provincial civil aviation authorities have
invested 88 million yuan in the renovation and the expansion of
airport facilities and other services.
</P>
<P>
These projects included renovation and expansion of the runway
and parking apron, and decoration and expansion of the terminal
building and an airport hotel, construction of a navigation tower,
improvement of its lighting system for night flights, and
installation of 400 lines of program-controlled telephones.
</P>
<P>
Newly established services include a computerized ticket
reservation system that is connected with other systems
nationwide, consignment of cargoes for international transport,
express mail, and so on.
</P>
<P>
With improved infrastructure, annual passenger and cargo flows
at the Guiyang airport have risen 30 percent and 20 percent,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The airport opened charter flights to Hong Kong, the first
destination for its routes outside the Chinese mainland, in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Last year the airport handled 9,600 flights, three times the
number in 1990, 850,000 passengers and 9,000 tons of cargo and
mail.
</P>
<P>
To boost its air traffic, a second airport with a total
investment over one billion yuan is being built in the city, and
is scheduled to go into operation next year.
</P>
<P>
Then air passenger and cargo flows to and from Guiyang are
expected to increase by some 60 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
