<HEADLINE> South Korean Lawmaker Arrested on Election Law Violation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 13 (Xinhua) -- An opposition member of the South
Korean parliament has been arrested on charges of buying "clapping
supporters" during the general election campaign.
</P>
<P>
Park Kyu-shik from the United Liberal Democrats (ULD), is the
first sitting member of parliament to be arrested for breaking
election laws, although nearly one third of the lawmakers who won
seats in Thursday's election are under investigation.
</P>
<P>
Park allegedly spent 15,000 U.S. dollars during
his election campaign on getting "clapping supporters" to attend a
speech session in Seoul on March 29. He is also alleged to have
spent 7,500 dollars on buying meals for voters.
</P>
<P>
Park's four aides, also under detention, confirmed that the
lawmaker instructed them to give out money, a prosecution official
said.
</P>
<P>
The official disclosed that 97 lawmakers-elect, 32.4 percent of
the total 299 legislators, are under investigation for various
violations of the election law.
</P>
<P>
In the recent South Korean National Assembly elections held on
April 11, the ruling New Korea Party won 139 seats, the National
Congress for New Politics 79 seats, the ULD 50 seats, the
Democratic Party 15 seats and independents 16 seats. 
</P>
</TEXT>
