<HEADLINE> Sampras, Chang Reach Salem Tennis Open Final </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Chinese-American Michael Chang
moved a step closer to his quest to the Salem Open title for the
third straight year by defeating Australian Todd Woodbridge in the
semi-finals on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Top seed Pete Sampras, who aims to regain the world number one
ranking, also reached the final by beating Jan Siemerink from the
Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
As the most favorite player of local fans, Chang did an easy
job of 6-3, 6-4 compared with his wins in the previous rounds,
while Sampras downed Siemerink 6-3, 6-4, 7-6 (7-2).
</P>
<P>
Sampras could regain the number one spot if he beats Chang on
Sunday for the 10th time in 17 career meetings.
</P>
<P>
But the rankings will also depend on how Austrian Thomas
Muster, the current number one, fares in Estoril where he has
reached the semi-finals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
