<HEADLINE> Roundup: PC Selection Committee Panel Holds Advice-Seeking Meetings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The Selection Committee Panel
of the Preparatory Committee (PC) of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR) held eight meetings here today to
seek advice from Hong Kong people on the methods of producing
Selection Committee members.
</P>
<P>
About 400 delegates from over 160 associations and
organizations attended today's meetings, including chambers of
commerce, associations of trade, tourism and banks, accounting and
labor agencies, trade unions, grass-root societies and district
organizations.
</P>
<P>
Vice-chairmen of the Preparatory Committee Lu Ping, Zhou Nan,
Tung Chee-hwa and Li Fook-sean were present at some of the
meetings.
</P>
<P>
During the consultations, delegates were active at voicing
their suggestions on the qualification and representativeness of
the members of the Selection Committee which is to be responsible
for selecting first chief executive and provisional legislative
council.
</P>
<P>
Some of the delegates elaborated on the general principle for
choosing Selection Committee members while others presented their
concrete views on the subject. Many of them handed over their
written suggestions after their speeches.
</P>
<P>
Most of the speakers at the meetings claimed that the members
of the Selection Committee must support the Basic Law and endorse
the related decisions made by the HKSAR Preparatory Committee,
adding that it should be set as a basic condition for the
qualification of the members.
</P>
<P>
Some of the delegates stressed the Selection Committee should
embody broader representativeness which finds manifestation in
adhering to the fundamental and long-term interests of Hong Kong
citizens, the principle of "one country, two systems" and "Hong
Kong people running Hong Kong," and efforts to promote Hong
Kong's smooth transition, long-term prosperity and stability.
</P>
<P>
They called for taking into account the interests of various
sectors and layers so that the Selection Committee could
represent the will of the masses of Hong Kong people.
</P>
<P>
Chui Kwok Kan, chairman of Hong Kong Mass Transit Railway Staff
General Association, said that he and his fellow staff stood for
setting it a basic condition to support the Basic Law and the
establishment of the Provisional Legislative Council for choosing
Selection Committee members.
</P>
<P>
Tsang Hin-chi, PC member and chairman of the Chinese General
Chamber of Commerce, said that the advice-seeking program in Hong
Kong is significant to PC's work in the coming months as well as
helpful to the formation of the Selection Committee.
</P>
<P>
Tsui Sze-min, PC member and publisher of the monthly Mirror
magazine, said that the advice-seeking meetings will promote the
exchanges between the preparatory committee and the Hong Kong
residents.
</P>
<P>
He said that absorbing advice from various sectors will bring
Hong Kong people's wisdom to full play in the preparatory work for
the establishment of the HKSAR.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
