<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-13 14:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Develop High-Quality Housing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, April 13 (Xinhua) -- China will focus on developing
high-quality housing in the next five years, to attain the goal of
14 sq m of living area for each person at the end of the century.
</P>
<P>
China will build 1.2 billion sq m of housing between 1996 and
2000, and renovate 40 million sq m of dilapidated houses.
</P>
<P>
The figures were released by the Ministry of Construction at a
national conference on construction planning, which was concluded
Friday in this capital city of south China's Hainan Province.
</P>
<P>
Construction of housing for ordinary families is of more
importance to China than development of commercial mansions and
villas, said an official with the ministry.
</P>
<P>
Having one of the world's fastest-growing economies, China has
been swept by a real estate craze with the rising demand for
business buildings in recent years, manifested by the mushrooming
highrises in big cities and luxurious villas in scenic areas.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, many ordinary Chinese are still plagued with
the problem of a lack of proper housing, especially in big
cities. For many Chinese, a proper house is their biggest lifelong
ambition.
</P>
<P>
Realizing the significance of ordinary housing, China's
policy-makers have taken macro-economic control measures to cool
down the real estate market, which has shown signs of unrestrained
and unbalanced growth since many building projects have been
driven by speculation and profiteering.
</P>
<P>
Last year's growth rate in China's real estate market was
roughly the same as in 1994, and the area of ordinary housing
development projects accounted for over 80 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
Much attention should be paid to the improvement of houses'
functions and living surroundings in housing projects, said Li
Zhendong, vice-minister of construction.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
