<HEADLINE> Lebanese PM, FM Leave for Damascus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik
Al-Hariri and Foreign Minister Fares Boueiz Left here this
afternoon for Damascus to meet Syrian leaders on continuous
Israeli aggressions in Lebanon which have entered its third
successive day.
</P>
<P>
A Syrian-Lebanese enlarged summit, which had been scheduled to
be held in Damascus today, was postponed due to the Israeli
escalations.
</P>
<P>
Hariri and Boueiz left Beirut after they had their second
meeting in few hours with President Elias Hrawi. House Speaker
Nabih Berri attended the first meeting in the Beirut Presidential
Palace this morning.
</P>
<P>
Before the second meeting in the Presidential Palace, the
foreign minister announced that he had made a contact with the
Lebanese representative in the United Nations on lodging a
complaint with the Security Council against the Israeli
aggressions.
</P>
<P>
He said he had also held a contact with the Lebanese
representative in the Arab league and instructed him to ask an
urgent session of the Arab League in order to put an end to the
Israeli aggressions against Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Boueiz said that contacts with Lebanese envoys to other
countries were being intensively conducted.
</P>
<P>
He added that he would call meetings today and tomorrow with
diplomatic envoys of the five permanent member states of the
U.N. Security Council, member states of the European Union and
the Arab League and other countries in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese Foreign Minister Boueiz announced earlier, after the
first meeting with Lebanon's three top leaders, that his country
had decided to lodge a complaint with the U.N. Security Council
against Israel's continuous aggressions.
</P>
<P>
And Lebanon made this decision when Israel was continuing air
raids and bombardments at southern Lebanese villages.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Boueiz expected that the United States would
use its "veto" right on holding a meeting of the Security
Council, or on any resolution the council could adopt.
</P>
<P>
"But we should hold the Security Council its responsibility,
and we will never accept a current logic that the (Israeli)
aggressions contribute in consolidating the peace process," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"There is no justifications at all for the Israeli attacks at
Lebanon and its aggressions against Lebanon's territories and
people."
</P>
<P>
Boueiz accused the Jewish state of attempting "to throw
Lebanon into confusion on the political, economic and social
levels, and to push the country to a confrontation with the
resistance movement."
</P>
<P>
He announced that he would summon in the Foreign Ministry a
meeting of representatives of Arab and International
organizations and institutions to support, socially, healthily and
 humanitarianly, the southern Lebanese villagers dispelled by the
Israeli aggressions from their houses in the past two days.
</P>
<P>
He said that contacts and coordinations were "continuing with
a number of countries in a purpose to put an end to the
Israeli aggressions, and to prevent any (Israeli) candidate from
benefitting from these mistakes in the (upcoming Israeli)
elections." 
</P>
</TEXT>
