<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-13 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vice-Premier Urges Shift in Agricultural Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier Jiang
Chunyun has said that two fundamental shifts in the economic
system and economic growth mode are the key to the fulfillment of
China's agricultural development goals for the next 5-to-15 years.
</P>
<P>
Jiang made this remark during an inspection tour of the Chinese
capital from April 10 to 12.
</P>
<P>
The two shifts, namely from a centrally-planned economy to a
market one and from a quantity-oriented extensive economic growth
pattern to a quality-oriented intensive one, should be combined
organically so as to further liberalize and develop the
agricultural productive forces, Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
Accompanied by Wei Jianxing, Party secretary of Beijing, Mayor
Li Qiyan, and Agriculture Minister Liu Jiang, the vice-premier
inspected suburban Tongxian County and the Fangshan District.
</P>
<P>
In Hugezhuang Township, Tongxian County, Jiang told local
farmers that the development of greenhouse vegetables is both an
effective way for them to become prosperous and an effective
measure for the city to supply sufficient vegetables round the
year.
</P>
<P>
He also highly appraised the successful experience of three
villages in the Fangshan District in developing agriculture,
animal husbandry, forestry and rural industry in accordance with
the actual conditions of their respective areas.
</P>
<P>
On Friday afternoon Jiang was briefed on the capital's work and
achievements in promoting the "rice bag" and "vegetable basket"
projects. He said that Beijing, with a large urban area and
relatively small suburban area, has scored marked progress in
reinforcing and developing agriculture. Statistics show that last
year the capital's total rural output value and the per capita
income of farmers increased by 10 percent and 39 percent
year-on-year, respectively.
</P>
<P>
"The acceleration of the development of agriculture and the
rural economy lies in promoting the two shifts," Jiang said. "The
two shifts amount to a profound revolution, which may naturally be
challenged by the cropping up of new situations and problems."
</P>
<P>
Whether or not the problems can be overcome in time and
effectively depends on whether officials at all levels, especially
leading ones, can keep up with new developments in perception and
ideology, Jiang said, urging all rural officials to continue to
emancipate their minds.
</P>
<P>
He said that while efforts should be made to stabilize the
current household contract responsibility system, the scale of
agro-business should be increased gradually, adding that
appropriate economies of scale should be permitted in areas where
the conditions are ripe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
