<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Restores Ancient Walled Village </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 13 (Xinhua) -- A restored ancient walled
village named Kun Lung Wai in Fanling, the New Territories of Hong
Kong, was opened to public today following a rehabilitation
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The walled village was one of the five wais (walled villages)
and six tsuens (villages) established by the Tangs who settled in
Lung Yeuk Tau, Fanling, in the 14th century. Of the five walled
villages, Kun Lung Wai is the best preserved.
</P>
<P>
Built in 1744, Kun Lung Wai is surrounded by thick brick walls
on four sides, with a watch tower at each corner and a communal
shrine at the farthest end to the entrance gate.
</P>
<P>
The restoration project, with a cost of 4.8 million HK dollars
(620,000 US dollars), started in 1988 to rebuild the collapsed
walls. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
