<HEADLINE> India Continues Crackdown on Telephone Racket </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 13 (Xinhua) -- India's Central Bureau of
Investigation (CBI) is continuing to probe a telephone racket
involving the Mahanagar Telephone Nigam Limited (MTNL) in the
capital, the Press Trust of India reported today.
</P>
<P>
The CBI arrested an MTNL employee, identified as Ashok Rai, who
allegedly used to obtain telephone connections using forged
documents and sell it to people at exorbitant rates, a CBI
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Rai, who masterminded the whole racket, owned a four-storey
house in south Delhi and a garment manufacturing factory besides
having three telephone connections at his residence, the spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
When the anti-corruption branch of CBI Delhi unit raided his
premises, he tried to escape by jumping from the roof-top to the
adjacent house but was finally nabbed.
</P>
<P>
During the raids, the CBI team found a large number of
telephone instruments besides rubber stamps and letter-heads of
fake firms in whose names the accused secured the phone
connections.
</P>
<P>
The probe carried out so far revealed that Rai had issued over
50 connections using fake documents and about 20 such connections
were at present functioning in different parts of the capital.
Three factories in the capital were also searched and unauthorized
instruments installed there seized.
</P>
<P>
The investigating agency earlier detected a massive racket
involving long distance calls in which the bills, amounting to a
total of over 1.5 crore rupees (about 430,000 US dollars), were
passed on to various MTNL subscribers in south Delhi allegedly by
some private persons with the help of some MTNL employees.
</P>
</TEXT>
