<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-13 12:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Set to Conquer Iodine Deficiency: Scientist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 13 (Xinhua) -- After nearly three decades of
efforts, India is very close to conquering iodine deficiency that
affects millions, an eminent Indian scientist said today.
</P>
<P>
India is likely to meet the World Health Organization's goal of
eliminating the deficiency by the end of the century, professor V.
Ramalingaswamy, former director-general of Indian Council of
Medical Research (ICMR), said.
</P>
<P>
Delivering a keynote address at a symposium on iodine
deficiency disorders and thyroid diseases here, professor
Ramalingaswamy said "the historic decision of the government of
India to iodize all edible salt in a phased manner in 1990 can be
said to be the watershed in controlling iodine deficiency."
</P>
<P>
The professor, now working at the famous All India Institute of
Medical Sciences (AIIMS), said iodine deficiency disorder not only
causes goiter but also affects the brain of unborn babies.
</P>
<P>
Ramalingaswamy and his colleagues at AIIMS were the first to
show that the endemic goiter in India was due to deficiency of
iodine in the soil and waters of affected areas, and not due to
genetic factors or presence of goiter-causing factors in local
diet.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960413.0062 </DOCNO>
