<HEADLINE> Kim Vows to Continue Reform after Election "Victory" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 13 (Xinhua) -- South Korean President Kim
Young-sam said today he will do his utmost for the rest of his
term of office to "correct the country's history, refound the
nation and seek stability through reform."
</P>
<P>
Kim, leader of the ruling New Korea Party (NKP), made the
remarks at a lunch for Lee Hoi-chang, the NKP's campaign manager,
and other key members of the NKP in appreciation of their work
during the parliamentary election campaign.
</P>
<P>
In the 15th National Assembly elections held on Thursday, the
NKP won 139 of the 299 parliamentary seats, losing 11 of its 150
seats in the outgoing parliament and failing to maintain its
previous absolute majority.
</P>
<P>
The main opposition National Congress for New Politics (NCNP)
headed by Kim Dae-jung suffered a major setback as the 79 seats it
won fell far short of its goal of 100.
</P>
<P>
President Kim pledged to continue to work toward national
harmony and to eradicate malpractice and corruption.
</P>
<P>
He also called on party members to make continued efforts for
reforms while maintaining stability, saying that "the (ruling)
party will have to take humble attitudes towards the election
outcome and think over what the people need."
</P>
<P>
He said any wrongdoing and illegal activities in the elections
will have to be thoroughly investigated. "Those who violated
election laws will be punished whoever they are," Kim added.
</P>
<P>
During the 16-day election campaign, which ended on April 10,
502 people were found by the Central Election Management Committee
(CEMC) to have broken election laws. Of those, 15 were referred
for formal indictment, 63 to the police for further investigation,
and the remainder were let off with a warning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
