<HEADLINE> France Concerned Over Israeli Bombing of Lebanon: Chirac </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 13 (Xinhua) -- President Jacques Chirac said
Friday that France is seriously worried about the tense situation
in Lebanon following the Israeli bomb attacks there, the Elysee
Palace announced today.
</P>
<P>
During telephone conversations with U.S. President Bill Clinton
and Israeli Prime Minister Shimon Peres, Chirac said retaliation
bombing on Beirut suburbs and strongholds of the Hezbollah
guerrillas (Party of God) have escalated the conflict in the
region and could jeopardize the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Chirac appealed to all sides to show restraint and
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
Israel launched air attacks in southern Lebanon Friday in
retaliation for Hezbollah rocket attacks against centers of
population in northern Israel.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese government immediately asked for French
intervention following the air bombardment, according to press
reports.
</P>
<P>
In a separate development, French Foreign Minister Herve de
Charette sent private letters to Syrian Foreign Minister Faroul
Al-Charek and Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati on
Saturday, saying the French government is gravely concerned about
the situation in the region and asking all sides to exercise
restraint. 
