<HEADLINE> EU Accused of Financing Recent Fighting in S. Mogadishu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, April 13 (Xinhua) -- General Mohamed Farah Aidid
has accused foreigners of being involved in the recent fighting
in south Mogadishu between his supporters and those of Osman
Hassan Ali Atto.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with an African newspaper "the Hom" that Backs
his government published today, General Aidid pointed out that
Mr. Sigurd Illing, special envoy of the European Union to
Somalia, was among those involved deeply in the fighting.
</P>
<P>
The general also accused the European Union of financing the
civil war in south Mogadishu, saying, "even ordinary civilians
know how much money they have paid for refueling the fighting."
</P>
<P>
General Aidid claimed that what his political adversaries want
is to misguide the Somali people as "practised by the United
Nations and late dictator Mohamed Said Barre".
</P>
<P>
He said his government vowed to defend the Somali people from
what he called the foreign-manipulated elements who will be
"eradicated from the country very soon".
</P>
<P>
The General did not mention the name of Osman Atto but just
labelled his faction as an armed group who are "determined to
destablize the security of the capital and close the functioning
seaport of Merca so as to make the people further suffer."
</P>
<P>
This armed group has aligned themselves with the "manifesto
group", referring to Ali Mahdi's faction, which is "popular" in
what he called sympathizing with the imperialists and has "deep
hatred to the Somali sovereignty".
</P>
<P>
Speaking of his long presence in Baidoa and Bakol, Aidid who
returned to the capital last week said his tour to the Rahanwein
region was a complete success, saying the government forces have
restored law and order there and expelled 21 aid people who he
said were flinging mud at the legitimacy of his government.
</P>
<P>
He claimed the 21 aid workers he seized during his capture of
Baidoa last September, were caught attacking his government while
teaching the people of Baidoa christianity.
</P>
<P>
The relations between General Aidid and the world community
have been anything but good. The general has recently refused the
visit of a high-level delegation from the European Community to
south Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, he also banned Mr Sigurd Illing from visiting Somalia
without the consent of his government.
</P>
<P>
This is the first interview General Aidid gave to the media in
more than a year and this time he gave the interview to his
paper. He refused to meet all other journalists for reasons
unknown. 
</P>
</TEXT>
