<HEADLINE> China Holds Largest International Fashion Contest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Two Chinese designers won the
championship at the Fourth Brothers Cup Young Fashion Designers
Contest, the largest international fashion contest ever held in
China, in the finals held here this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Brothers Wu Xuewei and Wu Xuekan, from Heilongjiang Province,
presented an original fashion collection with the theme of
"Paper-Cut". Combining the traditional Chinese paper-cutting
patterns with smart suiting materials, their designs convey a
strong contrast between the old and new worlds. "These hand-made
garments are a reflection of the ideological dilemma all modern
people are facing," commented a fashion expert here.
</P>
<P>
Another fashion line, "Red Ladies" designed by 25-year-old
Belgian designer Vanessa Neirynck, won the second prize. The
designer said this collection is her personal vision of China. "I
have been working all in red with some touches of white and gold.
I think my inspiration is from China's red lanterns, textile
materials and the spirit of Chinese culture."
</P>
<P>
Thirty-six young designers from 17 countries and regions,
including China, Britain, France, Finland, Italy, Nigeria, Canada,
Singapore, Japan and Hong Kong, entered the finals after a
preliminary contest this morning.
</P>
<P>
The panel of judges was formed of 13 senior Chinese and foreign
fashion experts.
</P>
<P>
Li Xin, chairwoman of the selection board, said that the
contest aimed at promoting exchanges between the fashion cultures
of the East and West, and bringing more outstanding young
designers, who always enjoy less opportunities than the older
ones, into the limelight.
</P>
<P>
The annual contest received 1,132 entries from both at home and
abroad this time.  
</P>
</TEXT>
