<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Retail Prices Up 7.7 Percent in First Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- China's retail price index rose
7.7 percent on an annual basis during the first quarter of this
year, according to the State Statistics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
In March alone the retail price index rose 7.7 percent over the
same month of last year. The price level in March marked a rise of
0.2 percent from the previous month.
</P>
<P>
About half of the country succeeded in curbing retail prices at
or below the national average in March. In Shanghai, China's
biggest city, the retail price index rose 6.2 percent compared
with last year and its price level in March registered a slip of
0.2 percent from the previous month.
</P>
<P>
Also in March, Beijing and Tianjin saw their retail price
indices rise 9.7 percent and 8.1 percent, respectively, over the
same month of last year. Both cities' price levels were 0.4
percent lower than in February this year.
</P>
<P>
Hainan was the most successful province in bringing down
inflation in March. Its retail price index rose three percent over
the same month of last year. The price level in March went down by
0.5 percent from the previous month.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
