<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Freeze Issuing of Firearms Licenses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad said here today that his government has decided
to freeze the issuing of firearms licenses nationwide for an
indefinite period.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir told reporters that the decision was made by the Home
Affairs Ministry recently because too many license holders had not
been taking care of their firearms and losing them.
</P>
<P>
"We have sometimes been too lax (in issuing the licenses) and
too many people are losing their firearms. So we want to ensure
that only those who are eligible get the license," said Mahathir,
who is also minister of home affairs.
</P>
<P>
The freeze order came after Malaysian businessman Alfred Chin
was arrested in Taiwan for alleged arms smuggling last month.
Malaysian police confirmed that these arms were smuggled from the
State of Sabah, where, a report said, at least 15,000 firearms
licenses have been issued in the past.
</P>
<P>
Local reports also said some politicians might also be involved
in issuing firearms licenses and urged the authorities to make a
thorough investigation.
</P>
<P>
When asked if anyone found involved would be dealt with under
the internal security act, Mahathir said the decision would be
made only after police completed their investigation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
