<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-13 10:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2,500-year-old Tombs of Nomads Excavated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Two tombs belonging to a tribe
which roamed north China some 2,500 years ago have been unearthed
in Xinzhou City, Shanxi Province, according to the "China
Archeology News".
</P>
<P>
In one of the tombs local archaeologists found a three-layer
wooden coffin, 11 pieces of bronze ware and the remains of a
40-year-old female thought to have been buried alive with the
coffin occupant.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that it is hard to tell the sex of the coffin
occupant because the remains had decayed too much.
</P>
<P>
The system of the burial of live people along with the deceased
lasted up until the Ming Dynasty (1644-1911) in some parts of
China.
</P>
<P>
The other tomb contained three coffins. A female wearing
jewelry was buried in the middle one, while a couple and another
person lay separately on each side.
</P>
<P>
Seven pieces of bronze ware were found in the tomb.
</P>
<P>
The tombs, probably belonging to the Rong or Di nomadic tribes,
were found among a group of tombs dating back to the Spring and
Autumn Period (771-476 BC). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
