<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-13 10:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordanian-U.S. Joint Exercises Start Today </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Jordan announced here today the
joint Jordanian-U.S. military exercises "Eager Tiger" starts
today.
</P>
<P>
Major General Mahammed Abadneh, Chief of Staff of Royal
Jordanian Air Force, said at a press conference that 1,100
American servicemen and 34 U.S. planes arrived here Friday will
start joint military exercises with Jordanian air forces.
</P>
<P>
However, he did not give the number of Jordanian pilots who
will take part in the exercises.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference here today with the Commander of
the U.S. expeditionary forces, General Bill Loony, he said the
Jordan's joint military exercises with the United States are not
new, noting that Jordan has held similar exercises with friendly
forces, including the U.S. air forces since 1991.
</P>
<P>
He added that what is new about this year's exercises is its
coincidence with the deployment of American aircraft in Jordan to
monitor the U.N. imposed "no-fly zone" over southern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the surveillance flights over southern Iraq
would not be launched directly from Jordan.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that neither Jordanian pilots nor any other
air force would take part in the surveillance flights, which
had to be launched from land two months instead of Gulf-based
aircraft carriers because of the temporary absence from the
region of an aircraft during that period.
</P>
<P>
Looney said the 34 U.S. planes and 1,100 servicemen are not
in Jordan to provide support to the temporary mission, which
he said would last until sometime in June.
</P>
<P>
The planes participating in the exercises and surveillance
flights are 18 F-16s, 12 F-15s and 4 KC-135 tanker jets,
according to the daily Jordan Times today.
</P>
<P>
The American contingent, named "Airpower Expeditionary Force"
will also carry out some repairs at the air base so as to enable
the base to receive F-16s that Jordan is expected to receive this
year from the United States in line with the assistance package
between the two countries, Prime Minister Abdul Karim Kabariti has
said.
</P>
<P>
It is widely expected that the U.S. planes will use the
airspace of Saudi Arabia to enter Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The surveillance flights are also scheduled to start today.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time Jordan allows itself to be used as a
launching base for the surveillance flights over southern Iraq
since the "no-fly zone" was declared down 32nd parallel by the
U.N. Security Council in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The "no-fly zone" aimed at protecting Shiite Moslem rebels in
southern Iraq who rose up against the Saddam regime in the wake
of the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
Jordan has reiterated that the Kingdom would not be a party to
any military operations against Iraq and would not allow its
territory to be used in any strike on its east neighboring country.
</P>
<P>
The surveillance flights, Jordanian officials said, come in
line with the U.N. resolutions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
