<HEADLINE> Lebanon to Lodge Complaint with U.N. Against Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Foreign Minister Fares
Boueiz announced here this morning, after a meeting with
Lebanon's three top leaders, that his country has decided to lodge
a complaint with the U.N. Security Council against Israel's
continuous aggressions.
</P>
<P>
In the presence of the foreign minister, Lebanese President
Elias Hrawi, House Speaker Nabih Berri and Prime Minister Rafik
Al-Hariri held a meeting in the Beirut Presidential Palace this
morning, to consult on the present situations in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
And Lebanon made this decision when Israel was continuing air
raids and bombardments at southern Lebanese villages.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Boueiz announced that his country "has
decided to file a complaint with the U.N. Security Council against
the recent Israeli aggressions."
</P>
<P>
He said that he would conduct contacts with the council
members. Among the five permanent members of the Security
Council, the United States has reportedly expressed a "negative
position" on any call for a council meeting, according to an
earlier statement by Boueiz.
</P>
<P>
At the end of today's meeting of the Lebanese leaders, the
foreign minister also called for an urgent meeting of the Arab
League, in an addition to other international consultations.
</P>
<P>
He expected that the United States would use its "veto" right
on holding a meeting of the Security Council, or on any resolution
the council could adopt.
</P>
<P>
"But we should hold the Security Council its responsibility,
and we will never accept a current logic that the (Israeli)
aggressions contribute in consolidating the peace process," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"There is no justifications at all for the Israeli attacks at
Lebanon and its aggressions against Lebanon's territories and
people."
</P>
<P>
Boueiz accused the Jewish state of attempting "to throw
Lebanon into confusion on the political, economic and social
levels, and to push the country to a confrontation with the
resistance movement."
</P>
<P>
He announced that he would summon in the Foreign Ministry a
meeting of representatives of Arab and International
organizations and institutions to support, socially, healthily and
humanitarianly, the southern Lebanese villagers dispelled by the
Israeli aggressions from their houses in the past two days.
</P>
<P>
He said that contacts and coordinations were "continuing with
a number of countries in a purpose to put an end to the Israeli
aggressions, and to prevent any (Israeli) candidate from
benefitting from these mistakes in the (upcoming Israeli)
elections." 
</P>
</TEXT>
