<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: No Israeli Air Raids over Last Night, Bombardments Continue (by Shao Jie) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 13 (Xinhua) -- No Israeli air raids at targets in
Lebanon taken place since 10 pm (19:00 GMT) last night and until
this morning, but the Israeli forces were continuing bombarding
southern Lebanese villages.
</P>
<P>
Thunders and Lightnings have been raging in the sky over
Lebanon since last night, and a rainstorm has been poured down on
this country. Lebanese army sources saw that the bad whether
forced the Israeli forces to temporarily stop the air raids.
</P>
<P>
Reports from the south said that the Israeli forces were
continuing making reinforcements to the Israeli self-proclaimed
"security zone" in south Lebanon, and threatened to launch more
strikes at the Lebanese pro-Iranian Hezbollah or Party of God.
</P>
<P>
But a newest report from the south said that around 10:50 am
(7:50 GMT), Israeli warplanes launched an air raid at the
southern Lebanese villages of Haris, Zidqin and Shaitiyeh, in
which the Israeli planes launched air-to-surface missiles, but no
casualties were mentioned.
</P>
<P>
A Syrian-Lebanese enlarged summit, which had been scheduled to
be held in Damascus today, was cancelled due to the deteriorating
situations.
</P>
<P>
And Lebanon's three top leaders, namely President Elias Hrawi,
House Speaker Nabih Berri and Prime Minister Rafik Al-Hariri are
due to hold a meeting, in the presence of Foreign Minister Fares
Boueiz, today to consult on the situations.
</P>
<P>
Well-informed sources expected that the Lebanese leaders would
discuss the latest developments in light of the Israeli
aggressions against Lebanon, which have entered their third
successive day, and study lodging a Lebanese complaint with the
U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
And they would also review outcomes of current diplomatic
activities in a purpose to put an end to the Israeli military
escalation.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese leaders would make an assessment on results of
the diplomatic contacts on various levels, including one made by
Prime Minister Rafik Al-Hariri with French President Jacques
Chirac in which, the well-informed sources said, Chirac briefed
Hariri the former's contact with U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
House Speaker Nabih Berri, in a statement issued today,
ironically pointed out that Israel did not need to make an excuse
by announcing a violation (by the Hezbollah) of the so-called
"July understanding," a U.S.-mediated tacit agreement which put an
end to an Israeli blitz in South Lebanon in July, 1993.
</P>
<P>
He noted that no matter whether the July understanding would
remain or collapse, Israel was determined to expand its
aggressions in Lebanon in a bid to press for the Israeli
conditions and to use Lebanon to exert more pressure upon Syria.
</P>
<P>
Under the July understanding, Israel promised to refrain from
attacking civilian targets in Lebanon in exchange for a hezbollah
guarantee on security of the Jewish settlements in northern Israel.
</P>
<P>
After making a telephone contact on Friday night with French
Foreign Minister Herve De Charette, Lebanese Foreign Minister
Boueiz received a call from his Egyptian counterpart Amr Moussa.
</P>
<P>
Boueiz expressed a fear on an Israeli attempt to enlarge the
buffer zone in South Lebanon in order to make it wider than the
range of the (Hezbollah's) Katyusha rockets.
</P>
<P>
He accused the U.S. administration of adopting a "negative
position" toward any call for a meeting of the U.N. Security
Council.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli occupation forces are continuing its
bombardments in South Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Security sources in the south reported that the Israeli forces
at 7:15 am (4:15 GMT) bombarded the village of Yater and an area
between the towns of Jibshit and Shukin. And earlier bombardments
at southern Lebanese villages led to the wounding of two
civilians.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese army sources reported that Israel carried out 40 air
raids at targets in Lebanon Friday, 30 of which targeted southern
Lebanese areas, and two others aimed at Beirut's south suburbs.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the Syrian forces in Lebanon announced that one
Syrian soldier was killed and seven others were wounded in an
Israeli air raid at a Syrian position at Beirut's south suburbs on
Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Syrian troops in the area fired anti-air
weapons at the Israeli planes and "forced them to escape."
</P>
<P>
And Israeli forces also fired 3,500 heavy artillery shells at
some 60 places in south Lebanon Friday, the Lebanese army sources
said.
</P>
<P>
Thirteen Lebanese died and more than 30 were wounded in
Friday's Israeli aggressions, adding the casualties in the past
two days to 18 killed and more than 45 wounded.
</P>
<P>
Guerrillas of the Shiite fundamentalist Hezbollah fired back
by firing Katyusha rockets at Jewish settlements in northern
Israel, wounding some eight Israeli residents at Kyriat Shmona.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the Israeli air force threatened that his air
force would carry out more strikes "if that is necessary." He
announced that the Israeli warplanes had attacked 14 Hezbollah
targets, claiming that they would destroy any vehicle moving in
southern Lebanese villages.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli army had ordered local residents of 41 southern
Lebanese towns and villages to leave their house before 4:30 pm
(13:30 GMT) on Friday afternoon, forcing about 100,000 local
Lebanese residents to escape to Saida, Sour and other safer
places.
</P>
<P>
But Israeli forces started the bombardments before the time
</P>
</TEXT>
