<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-13 09:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Businessmen Urged to Promote Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 13 (Xinhua) -- President Benjamin Mkapa
has urged the indigenous business community to take advantage of
the country's rich natural endowments and translate them into a
better life for the people.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a dinner hosted by the Tanzania Chamber of
Commerce, Industry and Agriculture here on Friday, Mkapa said it
was individuals, groups or institutions that could make Tanzania
a better or worse place to live in.
</P>
<P>
"God the Almighty has been kind to us giving us a beautiful
country, richly endowed with resources, geographically well
positioned and above all, a country at peace with its neighbors
and itself," he observed.
</P>
<P>
President Mkapa pointed out that these advantages should be
translated into a better life for the people.
</P>
<P>
He said the appeal was intended to awaken the indigenous
businessmen to their responsibility of building a truly national
economy.
</P>
<P>
"We need foreign investment because we can't do without
foreign capital, technology and markets, but foreign investors
have their own countries, and are not here for charity," he said,
pointing out that whereas foreigners will eventually return to
their countries of origin, tanzanians will remain with whatever
they contributed to make the Tanzania of tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
The president added that the pursuit of short-term individual
benefits should not blind the people to their responsibilities
for long-term development and prosperity of the national economy.
</P>
<P>
He noted whereas it was true that profit and large fortunes
constituted strong motivation for entrepreneurship and business,
indigenous Tanzanians should embrace the public good.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa called for a genuine partnership between the business
community and the government so as to develop a truly national
economy.
</P>
<P>
He said he needed full support of the private sector in his
crusade against corruption because great corruption that is
eating away the country's economy revolves around business
people.
</P>
<P>
The business community has urged the government to rationalize
the taxation system and change would be seen in the next budget,
said Mkapa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
