<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-13 09:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Tea Production Drops Last Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Uganda's tea production dropped
by 768 tons in 1995 while exports fell by 289 tons in comparison
with those of 1994, reported the local daily "the New Vision"
today.
</P>
<P>
A 1995 report on the tea industry by Uganda Tea Authority was
quoted as attributing the fall in production to shortage of
labor, drought, lack of fertilizers and inputs and high
production costs.
</P>
<P>
The country's tea production in 1995 was 12,692 tons,
including 3,445 tons of Uganda Tea Growers Corporation, 3260 tons
of Rwenzori Highlands Tea Company, 2,807 tons of Toro and Mityana
Tea Company Ltd, 1,962 tons of Uganda Tea Corporation and the
rest 1,218 tons, while the production in 1994 was 13,460 tons.
</P>
<P>
Tea exports in 1995 were 10,682 tons while the figure for 1994
was 10,971 tons.
</P>
<P>
Despite the fall in last year's crop, the report predicts a
boom in this year's production and exports.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the industry has been hampered by
uncompleted rehabilitation of relatively small private tea
estates which account for 22 percent of tea production in the
country.
</P>
<P>
"This group stillna limps due to lack of support from financial
institutions and source," said the report, it also points out the
high duty and taxes on tea machinery spares, leaf bags and other
inputs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960413.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-13 09:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Now World's 3rd Largest Elevator Manufacturer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The more than 30,000 elevators
that are produced each year in China, mean that it has become the
third largest manufacturer in the world, after the United States
and Japan, "China Machinery and Electronics" has reported.
</P>
<P>
This is a great leap forward from the 10,000 elevators produced
in the 30 years from 1949, when New China was founded, to 1979,
when the reform and opening up policy was initiated.
</P>
<P>
What is even more important is that China is now capable of
large-scale production of more sophisticated elevators, the paper
says.
</P>
<P>
However, it notes that both the quality and quantity of
domestic elevators still cannot meet domestic demand because the
country is also the largest elevator market in the world.
</P>
<P>
To make up for that shortcoming, China has to spend more than
400 million US dollars each year in importing 7,000 to 8,000
elevators, and imports of spare parts are also enormous.
</P>
<P>
To improve the quality of elevator production and maintenance,
the Chinese government has published its "Provisional Regulations
for Better Management of Elevators", imposing stiff requirements
on manufacture, installation, and maintenance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
