<DOCNO> XIE19960413.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-13 08:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dismissed Worker Wins Lawsuit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DALIAN, April 13 (Xinhua) -- A worker in this coastal city in
northeast China's Liaoning Province has won a lawsuit against his
former employer and been compensated for wrongful dismissal.
</P>
<P>
Qu Shiwei, a contracted worker, was fired by the Dalian Zhongce
Rubber Co. Ltd for failing to show up for work for 58 consecutive
days in February last year.
</P>
<P>
However, Zhongce failed to notify Qu of the decision within
seven days, nor did it transfer Qu's personal file and other data
to the unemployment insurance institution of the area where he has
a residence permit. Both of which are mandatory according to local
labor regulations.
</P>
<P>
Zhongce did not complete the required process until mid-January
this year, a delay of 90 days, preventing Qu from claiming
unemployment benefit for months.
</P>
<P>
On February 6 this year, Qu filed a complaint with the labor
dispute arbitration bureau of his district, demanding compensation
for loss of unemployment benefit for 24 months.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month the arbitration bureau reached a verdict,
holding Zhongce accountable for the economic loss Qu had suffered,
some 4,134 yuan (about 500 US dollars) in all.
</P>
<P>
Observers say that as China shifts to a market economy, Chinese
enterprises must be careful to strictly observe laws and
regulations, or they will be brought to justice accordingly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
