<DOCNO> XIE19960413.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-13 08:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese More Ready to Change Jobs (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DALIAN, April 13 (Xinhua) -- When it comes to changing or not
changing a job, it may take a Chinese father years to understand
his daughter.
</P>
<P>
Dian Chunling, a 26-year-old girl who has already changed her
job three times in the five years since her graduation from
college, said that she feels better each time after a change of
job.
</P>
<P>
"I'm quite satisfied with my present work," said Dian, who now
works as a beauty counselor in a cosmetics company in this, her
hometown in the northeastern Chinese province of Liaoning.
</P>
<P>
Dian recalled that her father, Dian Yalin, was firmly opposed
to her decision of leaving the Dalian Steel Wire Plant, her first
employer and a state-owned enterprise, nearly five years ago.
</P>
<P>
The elder Dian, 54, has worked at the Dalian Second Machine
Tool Plant since he was 19. He did not come to understand his
daughter's dissatisfaction with her job until his own plant was
merged by a local competitor last year, realizing jobs can be
insure.
</P>
<P>
Observers say that the time-honored tradition of being faithful
to "one job for life" is being smashed in China. Even the people
of the older generation are becoming less loyal to their jobs.
</P>
<P>
Such a change in people's attitude can be felt even on a city
bus. In the past people used to greet each other with "How about
your work unit?" But today people ask, "Do you still work at the
same unit?".
</P>
<P>
Teng Yupin, 50, was a government employee until China launched
its reform and opening-up drive in the late 1970s. Eager to
embrace the country's drive for a market economy, he then "dived
into the sea of business" as chief representative in Dalian of a
company headquartered in south China's island province of
Hainan. Today he is a deputy manager of the local Caesar's Palace
Night Club.
</P>
<P>
"A change of work environment enables me to learn something
new," Teng said.
</P>
<P>
In the old days of the centrally-planned economy, a Chinese
employee was dependent on his unit -- the enterprise for which he
worked -- for almost everything, ranging from old-age pension to
medical insurance.
</P>
<P>
As China shifts to a market economy and reforms its social
security system, gone are the days when work units provided a
comprehensive social security umbrella for their employees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960413.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-13 08:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese More Ready to Change Jobs (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Therefore, no matter how long Dian Yalin has worked for his
firm, he has to rely on a yet-to-mature social security regime for
his days after retirement, just like his daughter.
</P>
<P>
"Old-age pension has become something regardless of where and
how long you work, and this makes it unnecessary for job-hoppers
to worry about their wellbeing," Dian said.
</P>
<P>
In many parts of China, the social security institutions now
provide workers with old-age pensions and unemployment, medical,
injury and maternity insurance.
</P>
<P>
A government official reminded, however, that the end of the
"one job for life" concept relies much on the establishment and
perfection of a social security and employment system and new
capital and labor relations.
</P>
<P>
Observers say that the relationship between employee and
employer is now bonded by labor contracts, which were unknown to
Chinese until just two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Labor has revealed that 80 percent of Chinese
workers have signed labor contracts with their companies, and the
old system whereby employment was arranged by the government has
been replaced by a market-oriented employment system, under which
the employee and employer bargain individually.
</P>
<P>
Official data show that more and more Chinese have become ready
to change their jobs so long as such a change is beneficial to the
fulfilment of their personal wishes and ambitions.
</P>
<P>
"I'll not hesitate to change my job again if a more ideal one
crops up," Dian Chunlin said, quoting an ancient Chinese proverb
of "A tree may wither away provided it is moved, whereas a change
of job can make a human more vigorous and hopeful."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960413.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-13 08:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DPRK Insists on Signing Peace Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The Democratic People's
Republic of Korea (DPRK) insists on signing a peace treaty to
replace the armistice agreement signed at the end of Korean War in
1953, a DPRK foreign ministry spokesman said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The statement was regarded as a response to the reactions taken by
the United States and South Korea on the entrance of DPRK soldiers
into the Demilitarized Zone (DMZ) separating DPRK and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman accused the violations of the Armistice Agreement
by the United States and South Korea, especially the latest series
of large-scale military exercises, saying that it is the United
States and South Korea who should be responsible for the tension
in the Korean Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said in a written statement that his country will
continue to honor the armistice agreement till a new peace treaty,
which was proposed by the DPRK, is signed to replace the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
He said that the U.S. should adopt a prudent policy toward the
situation in the peninsula, adding that DPRK will persist in its
position on replacing the armistice agreement with a peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
DPRK announced on April 4 it would no longer maintain the
status of both the military demarcation line and the DMZ
stretching across the divided Korean peninsula. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
