<HEADLINE> FM: Israel Not to Confront Syrian Army in Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Foreign Minister Ehud Barak
said last night that Israel has no interest in striking the
Syrian army in Lebanon, but will continue to hit Hezbollah bases
wherever they are.
</P>
<P>
Barak made the statement on Israel Television. He said anyone
who objects to the hits should put an end to Hezbollah activities
against Israel. The foreign minister was apparently referring to
Syria's reluctance to rein in Hezbollah in accordance with the
understanding brokered by the U.S. in 1993 in the wake of Israel's
Operation Accountability.
</P>
<P>
In response to a Lebanese government call for negotiations,
Barak indicated that there is no point to hold a dialogue with the
Lebanese government until it takes steps to prevent the launching
of Katyusha attacks against Israel.
</P>
<P>
According to a Beirut report, the Lebanese Prime Minister
Rafik Al-Hariri called on Israel to discuss a resolution to the
situation. He spoke at a press conference that a political
solution should be found as the problem cannot be solved by
military means. He accused Israel of what he called a crazy war
which cannot lead to anywhere because it cannot destroy Hezbollah
or make Israeli border safer, but can only escalate the situation.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio reported that Israel continued attacking Hezbollah
 positions in south Lebanon through the night, only to stop over
midnight due to stormy weather.
</P>
<P>
Throughout the day yesterday, Israel launched a total of 16
attacks in south Lebanon and two missions in the Beirut area.
More artillery units were despatched to the north. 
</P>
</TEXT>
