<HEADLINE> Military Plane Crashes in N. Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- A four seater-military plane
crashed at kalongo airfield in kitgum, northern uganda on
Thursday, but nobody was killed.
</P>
<P>
A report reaching here today said that the plane with four
passengers and loaded with machine guns crashed shortly after
taking off at about 3:00 p.m. that day. Kalongo is 45 miles
southwest of Kitgum town.
</P>
<P>
The plane burst into flames and was burnt beyond recognition,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The four occupants escaped with minor injuried but the pilot
was admitted at nearby Kalong Mission Hospital.
</P>
<P>
The plane was leaving Kalongo for Moroto with an advance team
of Ugandan Vice-President Specioza Kazibwe, who was on a
three-day tour of northern Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Security sources here attributed the cause of the crash to a
rough short runway and mechanical problems, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The fighter plane was last week used in operations against the
rebels of the Lord's Resistance Army in Gulu district, over 300
kilometers north of here. 
</P>
