<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-13 07:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Report on Tin, CPO, Rubber Markets in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The tin price on the Kuala
Lumpur Tin Market (KLTM) ended the week slightly higher today but
trading was thin.
</P>
<P>
The tin price closed the week at 15.96 Malaysian ringgit (about
6.38 US dollars) per kilogram, one sen higher than that of last
week. The market was traded in a tight range throughout the week.
</P>
<P>
The highest price quoted this week was 15.98 ringgit (about
6.39 US dollars) per kilogram Tuesday and Wednesday but slid to
15.93 ringgit (about 6.37 US dollars) per kilogram Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The total turnover for the week fell to 477 tons from 494 tons
in the previous week, and the KLTM price differential to the
London Metal Exchange (LME) narrowed to a premium of 70 US dollars
per ton Friday against a premium of 95 US dollars previously.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian rubber market ended the week lower. The price
for May RSS1 fell nine sen to end the week at 365 sen (about 1.46
US dollars) per kilogram from last week's close of 374 sen (about
1.49 US dollars), while the SMR20 dropped 12 sen to 333.5 sen
(about 1.33 US dollars) per kilogram.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said there were some hopes that the prices would
rebound in the near term, and they expected some buying interests
from China and some other fresh demands from the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
The shortage of rubber supply due to the rainy season did not
help much to push prices upward as buyers were on the sidelines
waiting for the price to fall further, while suppliers held on to
their position waiting for higher prices.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile on the crude palm oil (CPO) market, the CPO physicals
ended the week weaker. The price for April South ended 10 ringgit
lower to 1,285 ringgit (about US 514 dollars) per ton.  
</P>
</TEXT>
