<HEADLINE> Death of Thai State Media Chief Mourned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The death of the assassinated
Thai state media chief Saengchai Sunthornwat was mourned by his
family members, friends and colleagues here today as the rest of
the nation were celebrating the Thai New Year of Songkran.
</P>
<P>
The 53-year-old director-general of the Mass Communication
Organization of Thailand (MCOT) was killed Thursday evening when
he was returning home in his car driven by his wife.
</P>
<P>
A gunman fired a single bullet through the left rear door
window of Saengchai's car before fleeing on a motorcycle. The
bullet pierced through his lung and cut a coronary artery.
</P>
<P>
Senior MCOT and government officials described Saengchai's
death as a great loss.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Banharn Silpa-Archa, who attended the bathing
rites for Saengchai Friday, said Saengchai "was a very talented
and creative person and his death is regrettable."
</P>
<P>
Banharn said his government had intended to extend Saengchai's
office for another term because he had proven to be an efficient
and capable administrator of the MCOT, a state enterprise that
operates TV channel 9, the Thai News Agency and a few FM and AM
radio stations.
</P>
<P>
Saengchai took up the post in June 1993.
</P>
<P>
Many people, including the police, speculate that a conflict of
interest could have occurred after Saengchai ordered changes in
the programming of TV and radio stations under the MCOT.
</P>
<P>
Saengchai was a well-known columnist on politics and world
affairs in the widely-circulated Thai Rath newspaper. He was also
popular for his column on the usage of English vocabulary and
idioms.  
</P>
</TEXT>
