<HEADLINE> Fruit Trees Fatten Farmers' Wallets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The planting of cash crop trees
such as date, apple, Chinese chestnut and walnut has enriched the
wallets of farmers in northwest China's Shaanxi Province as well
as improved the natural environment.
</P>
<P>
Shaanxi, which covers eight latitudes, is home to some 400
varieties of trees of economic value.
</P>
<P>
During the Eighth Five-year Plan (1991-1995) period, the area
of cash crop forests in the province increased at an annual rate
of 92,000 ha, accounting for some 35 percent of the new forest
areas. At present, there are 1.46 million ha of forests of
economic value in the province, which yield 4.2 billion yuan-worth
of output value a year.
</P>
<P>
The forestry construction is closely related with rural
economic development. In Hancheng City more than 4,000 rural
households each earn over 10,000 yuan, a handsome income for a
country with a per capita GNP of just over 800 US dollars, from
Chinese prickly ash trees every year.
</P>
<P>
To stimulate farmers' enthusiasm for planting trees, local
authorities encourage them to contract the rehabilitation of
barren mountains, sometimes for as long as 70 years. In Yan'an, a
veteran Communist revolutionary base, more than 66,000 barren
mountains have been afforested, half of which are covered by
apple, apricot and date trees.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
