<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Unearths Massive Telephone Racket </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 13 (Xinhua) -- India's Central Bureau of
Investigation (CBI) has detected a massive racket involving the
diversion of long distance telephone facility from genuine
subscribers to illegal telephone lines, the Hindustan Times
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Unaccounted bills of some 15 million rupees (about 430,000 US
dollars) were passed on to various subscribers of the Mahanagar
Telephone Nigam Limited (MTNL) in the southern part of the
capital.
</P>
<P>
The investigation followed a string of complaints from
subscribers to the MTNL in the last few months against excessive
billing and being charged for long distance calls they never made.
</P>
<P>
After days of undercover operations and sustained surveillance,
the CBI succeeded in detecting the telephone numbers and places
from where the calls were actually being made.
</P>
<P>
The bills were being diverted by at least four conniving MTNL
employees to subscribers who never made the calls.
</P>
<P>
The investigative agency raided the premises of a restaurant
and a communications center in south Delhi, where a large number
of incriminating documents were recovered and unauthorized
telephone lines were found installed.
</P>
<P>
The restaurant owner, allegedly the kingpin of the racket, has
absconded.
</P>
<P>
A CBI spokesman indicated that this could only be the tip of
the iceberg and that there were reports of similar rackets
thriving in other exchanges as well.
</P>
<P>
The probe into this malpractice would continue, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960413.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-13 06:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Vetoes Foreign Relations Authorization Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 12 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Friday vetoed controversial legislation that would have
reorganized the country's foreign affairs agencies and contains a
number of anti-Chinese provisions.
</P>
<P>
"This legislation contains many unacceptable provisions that
would undercut U.S. leadership abroad and damage our ability to
assure the future security and prosperity of the American people,"
Clinton said in a message to Congress.
</P>
<P>
"It would unacceptably restrict the president's ability to
address the complex international challenges and opportunities of
the post-Cold War era," he said.
</P>
<P>
Among the anti-Chinese provisions is an amendment to the Taiwan
Relations Act, which states that the Act supersedes the provisions
of the 1982 Joint Communique between China and the United States.
Clinton pointed out that the 1982 Communique has been "one of the
cornerstones of our bipartisan policy toward China for over 13
years."
</P>
<P>
"The ongoing management of our relations with China is one of
the central challenges of United States foreign policy, but this
bill would complicate, not facilitate, that task," he said.
</P>
<P>
The bill was designed to upgrade U.S. relations with Taiwan and
increase pressure on China in areas like human rights and Tibet,
which would have constituted gross violations of China's
sovereignty and interference in China's domestic affairs.
</P>
<P>
The provisions have been strongly opposed by the Chinese
government.
</P>
<P>
Clinton also objected to the limits set in the bill on U.S.
participation in international organizations.
</P>
<P>
The provisions are "at odds with ongoing discussions between
the Administration and the Congress aimed at achieving consensus
on these issues," he said.
</P>
<P>
"In its current form," he said, "the bill is inconsistent with
the decades-long tradition of bipartisanship in U.S. foreign
policy," and "would seriously impair the conduct of U.S. foreign
affairs."
</P>
<P>
This was the 14th time that Clinton had used his veto power
since becoming president in early 1993. Congress is not likely to
muster enough votes to override the veto. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
