<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-13 05:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis:  South Korean Parties to Race to Forge Alliances </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 12 (Xinhua) -- With no party securing a majority
in the South Korean general elections, competition is heating up
to woo new independent legislators.
</P>
<P>
The governing New Korea Party led by President Kim Young-sam
lost its majority in the National Assembly and is now faced with
the struggle of courting the 16 independent legislators to form a
majority in the new parliament to stabilize the rest of Kim's
five-year presidency.
</P>
<P>
The NKP won 139 seats in the general election, 11 less than it
had in the outgoing parliament and 11 short of an absolute
majority in the 299-seat National Assembly. The number was well
down on the 175 seats predicted by the nation's three major
television networks after polls closed on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
All 16 independents who stood were elected into office,
indicating that the major political parties are not fully trusted
by the public.
</P>
<P>
The ruling party in the 1988 and 1992 parliamentary elections
also failed to gain a majority, but succeeded in taking in the
independents and even opposition members.
</P>
<P>
However, this time it won't be easy for the NKP to woo the
independents. Apart from those in open conflict with the
ruling party, some independents like Won Yoo-chol, Park Jong-woo,
Hwang Sung-Kyun and Lim Jin-chul were forced to leave the NKP to
run in the election after their candidacies were denied.
</P>
<P>
One alternative for the NKP is to strike an alliance with the
minor Democratic Party (DP). The DP won only 15 seats, five seats
short to form a negotiation group in the National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the leading opposition party, the National Congress
for New Politics (NCNP) fell short of winning the one-third of
seats its leader Kim Dae-jung vowed he would use to force an
investigation into the funding of President Kim's 1992 campaign.
</P>
<P>
The NCNP won 79 seats, up from 55 at the last election but
fewer than the expected 100 seats which could cost 71-year-old Kim
Dae-jung the nomination for a fourth run for the presidency next
year.
</P>
<P>
Kim Dae-jung, Kim Young-sam's chief rival, accused the
president of using millions of dollars from a slush fund gathered
by his predecessor Roh Tae Woo, who is now on trial on bribery
charges.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said although the NKP lost its majority, Kim
Young-sam's internal and external policies are unlikely to change.
</P>
<P>
Four major political parties and 16 independents ran in the
parliamentary elections yesterday. The big winner seems to be the
conservative opposition, the United Liberal Democrats, led by
aspiring presidential candidate Kim Jong-pil. The party won 50
seats than the estimated 33. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
