<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Armed Forces Urged to Be Put Under  Caretaker Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi Defense Ministry
must be placed under the chief adviser of the caretaker government
to keep the armed forces above controversy, the country's former
largest opposition party -- the Awami (People's) League (AL) --
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
In a resolution issued after its presidium meeting Friday, the
AL said the president of the country had virtually expressed
no-confidence in the caretaker government by keeping the Defense
Ministry under himself.
</P>
<P>
It "is also contrary to the spirit of parliamentary democracy
and the constitution," said the resolution.
</P>
<P>
The Defense Ministry was placed under Prime Minister Begum
Khaleda Zia during the last regime of the Bangladesh Nationalist
Party (BNP) although President Abdur Rahman Biswas has kept the
post of the commander in chief of the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
After the caretaker government was set up last Wednesday
following the dissolution of the parliament and the resignation of
the prime minister, the Defense Ministry has been under the
president who is a member of the former ruling party.
</P>
<P>
The national armed forces would be controversial and lose its
image if they remain under the president, the AL resolution said,
adding that this has cast doubts among the people over the holding
of free and fair parliamentary polls.  
</P>
</TEXT>
