<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-13 05:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Extent of Damage at Chernobyl Remains Unclear </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Top experts from around the world
still have no conclusive figures concerning the damage caused by
the nuclear disaster at Chernobyl 10 years ago after a four-day
meeting here.
</P>
<P>
Some 1,000 politicians, experts and other delegates wound up
the meeting today on the aftereffects of the worst civilian
nuclear accident in history with appeals and recommendations for
tightening nuclear safety controls.
</P>
<P>
Although there was lack of decisive action, they did agree that
initial estimates may be too high on Chernobyl's impact on humans
and the environment.
</P>
<P>
Reading a closing statement, German Environment Minister Angela
Merkel, who presided over the meeting, said there is evidence
linking 31 deaths directly to the accident.
</P>
<P>
The toll was among firemen and personnel taking part in the
clean-up efforts immediately after a reactor at the Chernobyl
plant caught fire and exploded on April 26, 1986.
</P>
<P>
In addition, 237 people in the same group suffered various
radiation-related illnesses as high doses of radiation were
released from the reactor in Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
These casualty figures are much lower than those circulating in
the news media over the past decade.
</P>
<P>
However, participants of the meeting debated heatedly, but
failed to agree, on how many of others joining in the later stages
of clean-up operations have become victims.
</P>
<P>
In the closing statement, they called for decommissioning other
reactors that are still operational at the Chernobyl plant, and
constructing a second shield on the damaged No. 4 reactor.
</P>
<P>
The first shield on the reactor, built with cement right after
the accident to prevent further release of radioactive materials
into the air, may pose a long-term safety risk, they said.
</P>
<P>
According to experts, about 200 tons of nuclear fuels are still
in the reactor and part of them still active.
</P>
<P>
As to nuclear reactors similar to those at Chernobyl, or the
so-called PBMK reactors, the closing statement urged operators to
improve safety measures, so as to meet safety standards.
</P>
<P>
Fifteen PBMK reactors, mostly built by the former Soviet Union,
are still operational in Russia, Ukraine and Lithuania.
</P>
<P>
Merkel admitted that lack of financing has been a major factor
that makes countries involved reluctant to discuss the option of
shutting down all these reactors.
</P>
<P>
The just-concluded meeting was co-sponsored by the
International Atomic Energy Agency, the World Health Organization
and the European Commission to mark the 10th anniversary of the
Chernobyl disaster. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
