<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Indian Prime Minister P.V.
Narasimha Rao Friday ruled out any move to scale up the limit of
election expenses in the coming general elections, the Hindustan
Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
Rao made the remarks when asked at a press conference here
whether the government was inclined to raise the ceiling of
expenditure for parliamentary and assembly elections through an
ordinance.
</P>
<P>
"This is no time for any such action. If I do raise it, you
will be the first to criticize it," Rao replied.
</P>
<P>
Rao, also president of the ruling Congress Party, said the
expenditure ceiling and other matters relating to the elections
would have to be dealt with comprehensively and left to the new
Lok Sabha (lower house).
</P>
<P>
There has been a demand for raising the election expenses from
450,000 rupees (12,900 US dollars) to 1.5 million rupees (42,900
US dollars) for Lok Sabha candidates and from 150,000 rupees
(4,300 US dollars) to 600,000 rupees (17,200 US dollars) for
candidates contesting the assembly (state parliament) seats.
</P>
<P>
At the press conference, Rao also ruled out the possibility of
his retirement from active politics.
</P>
<P>
"There is no question of retirement because there are no
service rules in politics," he said.  
</P>
