<HEADLINE> Welding Work Responsible for Airport Fire: German Police </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Sparks from electric-welding tools
were the cause of the fire in Dusseldorf Airport, western Germany,
which killed 16 people and injured over 60 others, police said.
</P>
<P>
When the fire broke out, electric-welding equipment was being
used in the terminal building.
</P>
<P>
The sparks ignited plastic layers of some conduits and the fire
sent out thick acrid fumes containing poisonous and corrosive acid.
</P>
<P>
Police has started investigations on the culprit business and
will charge it with dereliction of duty, arson and manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
According to the local press, the 16 dead included seven
Germans, six French, two Italians and a Briton. Among the injured,
a German and a French are still in critical condition.
</P>
<P>
German President Roman Herzog and the federal government today
expressed their condolences to the families of the deceased.
</P>
