<HEADLINE> Thai Villagers Suspend Talks with Government Over  Land Rows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Villagers from northeastern
Thailand today broke off their talks with the Thai government over
land rows while demonstrators said they would stay in the capital
until the dispute is settled, the local press reported.
</P>
<P>
The Forum of Poor, which represents thousands of villagers in
northeastern Thai provinces, said it would not resume the talks
with the government unless local officials stop filling land in a
disputed area in Suphan Buri province.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting with the Prime Minister's Deputy Secretary-General
Jongchai Thiengtham, the villagers said they would stay in Bangkok
unless the government finds a new plot of land for them to
resettle.
</P>
<P>
Jongchai offered 16 million baht (640,000 US dollars) in
compensation for the villagers to move out but the villagers said
the sum was too small.
</P>
<P>
The villagers have been demonstrating in front of the
Government House for more than a week, demanding a swift solution
to their problems.
</P>
<P>
The trouble was triggered by local officials' plan to build a
new government center in Pho Kiew district, Suphan Buri province,
on the disputed land, which the villagers claimed belonged to them
before it was declared public land in 1984. 
</P>
