<HEADLINE> Poll Indicates Majority Have Hopeful Outlook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- The public continues to have
positive expectations about sustained stability in social
development this year, "China Daily" reported today.
</P>
<P>
More than 83 percent of those sampled in last November's survey
expected social development this year to be more or less as stable
as it was in 1995, suggested a survey conducted by researchers
with the State Commission for Economic Restructuring.
</P>
<P>
Since 1987, random samples have been taken every six months, in
40 cities throughtout 29 provinces, autonomous regions and
municipalities, said Sun Li, director of the Commission's Social
Survey System.
</P>
<P>
For each survey, Sun added, 2,000 families are selected, and
the selection is changed for each survey to diminish subjective
error.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey, the majority of respondents
anticipated that such major aspects of social life as economic
stability, the responsibility of the media and quality of consumer
goods would continue to improve this year.
</P>
<P>
More than one third of the respondents believed that their
family living standards would improve to a degree in 1996,
compared to a meagre 4.3 percent who expected a decline.
</P>
<P>
A bright future for reform was expected by about 70 percent of
those surveyed.
</P>
<P>
However, people were less pleased with economic development
last year than they were with development in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, 27 percent were satisfied with last year's
economic stability, a 7 percent rise over the year before.
</P>
<P>
The principal areas of dissatisfaction concern economic
stability, the quality of consumer goods, the rising prices and
the increasing gap among the people.
</P>
<P>
To alleviate these discontents, most people felt that direct
complaints or reports to the media were effective.  
</P>
</TEXT>
