<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hungary Warns Against Russian Interference With NATO  Membership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Hungarian Prime Minister Horn
Gyula said today that Russia has no right to intervene
over the issue of other states joining the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a joint press conference with his Polish
counterpart, Wlodzimierz Cimoszeicz, Horn said Hungary's decision
to join NATO is a matter of sovereignty and no other country has
the right to interfere.
</P>
<P>
Cimoszeicz told the press conference that Russia, which
has repeatedly expressed objection to NATO's eastward expansion, has
failed to show any change in its stand on the issue although
Poland, with its president's visit to Russia earlier this month, has
recently increased dialogue with Russia.
</P>
<P>
The Polish prime minister also stressed that no intervention
from a third country could prevent Poland and Hungary from joining
NATO.
</P>
<P>
On Hungarian-Polish ties, Horn said the two nations, which
wholeheartedly support European-Atlantic integration, will closely
cooperate in the process of entering the European Union.
</P>
<P>
Hungary enjoys close political and economic relations with
Poland. The trade volume between the two countries reached 550
million U.S. dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
The Polish prime minister, who arrived here today for a two-day
visit, has met Hungarian President Goncz Arpad and National
Assembly President Gal Zoltan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
