<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-13 02:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Millions of Chinese Tourists Flocking into Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- An increasing number of Chinese
tourists are flocking to the Sino-Vietnamese frontier areas,
thanks to the improvement of bilateral relations and the reopening
of the Beijing-Hanoi railway, According to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Statistics indicate that last year about 1.8 million Chinese
crossed the border for one-day tours of Mong Cai or Lang Son, and
many ventured further down to visit Hanoi and Ho Chi Minh City
(Saigon).
</P>
<P>
"Improved diplomatic relations between the two countries have
literally transformed the frontier areas from old battlefields to
a hot tourist destination," the English-language newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Easier travel, including the reopening of the railway between
Beijing and Hanoi in February for the first time since 1979, is
luring cross-border trekkers.
</P>
<P>
More and more domestic tourists are interested in touring the
frontier areas, especially those from Shanghai, Guangdong and
other coastal provinces, the newspaper quoted China Travel Service
guide Wang Hongji as saying.
</P>
<P>
In another development, an expressway from Guilin to Beihai,
via Nanning, is under construction in south China's Guangxi, an
autonomous region bordering Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
When the expressway is completed next year, it is expected that
200,000 French tourists and 180,000 US tourists in Vietnam will
also travel to Beihai and Guilin every year.
</P>
<P>
It also also reported that more than 10,000 Vietnamese tourists
visited China's Nanning, Guangzhou and Shanghai cities last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
