<DOCNO> XIE19960413.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-13 02:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier on Human Rights Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Chinese Premier Li Peng
said here today that China opposes the practice of interfering in
other countries' internal affairs by making use of the human
rights issue.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with French reporters here, Li said China and
other developing countries differ with Western countries over the
concept of human rights.
</P>
<P>
This, he said, is due to differences in culture and historical
traditions and different stages of economic development, and is
therefore not surprising.
</P>
<P>
He said China is willing to exchange views with Western
countries on human rights issues on the basis of equality and
mutual respect.
</P>
<P>
However, he stressed, China and other developing countries can
not tolerate interference in the internal affairs of other
countries under the pretext of human rights.
</P>
<P>
During the interview, the Chinese premier also answered a
question on the Taiwan issue.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated China's basic policy, saying that Beijing adheres
to the principle of "peaceful co-existence and one country, two
systems" but makes no commitment to give up the use of force to
solve the Taiwan issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
