<DOCNO> XIE19960413.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-13 02:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Management of Paging Industry to Be Strengthened </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 13 (Xinhua) -- Pocket pagers are becoming a new
source of noise pollution in China's urban areas, and people's
complaints, though not as loud as the beepers, show that these
pagers have become a part of city life, "China Daily" reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Since the Ministry of Posts and Telecommunications (MPT) gave
up the beeper monopoly several years ago, 2,136 private radio
paging stations have now been set up by non-telecom Chinese
enterprises, with a total of 11 million subscribers, compared with
7.3 million at the end of 1994.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the paper said, paging stations established by
telecommunications departments now have 17.4 million subscribers,
compared with 10.3 million in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The rapid growth in the sector has not come without cost. there
are too many paging stations, and fierce competition has led to
inefficient use of radio frequencies and increases in operating
cost, MPT officials were quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Some local authorities have suspended approval for new paging
stations.
</P>
<P>
According to a report in MPT-funded People's Posts and
Telecommunications News, south China's Guangdong Province now has
400 private radio paging stations and 5 million subscribers.
</P>
<P>
Most of these stations are small, with each having less than
10,000 subscribers.
</P>
<P>
In order to improve service and efficiency, the MPT is
encouraging the merger of paging stations.
</P>
<P>
Roaming service, which allows customers to move from city to
city without interruption of paging service, started this month on
a trial basis, and is available in 271 cities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
