<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Czech Team Claims to Have Found AIDS-Prevention Drug </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Czech scientists claim to have
found a drug which can prevent HIV from developing into full-blown
AIDS, a local news report said today.
</P>
<P>
The new drug, labelled only as (R)-PMPA, was discovered by
organic chemists and biochemists of the Czech Academy of Sciences
in collaboration with Belgian scientists, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It said that scientists in Seattle in the United States have
tested the drug and administered it to patients who have similar
symptoms to those of HIV-infected patients.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted An Holy, leader of the Czech research team
which discovered the drug, as saying that it will be produced by
the Gilead Sciences Company in California.
</P>
<P>
The new drug has been hailed by local press as the first and
only effective anti-AIDS drug. It will be widely used in a few
years' time, the report predicted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
