<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-13 01:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier: WTO Incomplete Without China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng said here
today that the World Trade Organization (WTO) is not true to its
name as China is still excluded from the organization.
</P>
<P>
WTO can not be referred to as a world trade body in real sense,
the premier said, as such a big trading power as China still has
not been accepted as one of its members.
</P>
<P>
Li made the remarks here this afternoon when he gave an
interview to French reporters.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese premier said it is unfair that China, which has a
population of 1.2 billion, has yet to be accepted by WTO.
</P>
<P>
Li explained that China is still a developing nation in terms
of per capita gross national product despite the remarkable
development of its economy.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, he said, the demand that China enter WTO in the
capacity of a developed nation is unfair and thus not acceptable.
</P>
<P>
China has lowered its general level of import tariffs from 35.9
percent to 23 percent, Li said, noting that the 36-percent
deduction rate is rare in the world.
</P>
<P>
He said that as its economy further develops, China will
continue to cut down its import tariffs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
