<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barkley, Richmond on Dream Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Charles Barkley of the Phoenix
Suns and Mitch Richmond of the Sacramento Kings are the choices to
fill the final two spots on the United States Olympic Basketball
squad, local reports said here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that that USA Basketball will name Barkley and
Richmond to join 10 other NBA stars in Atlanta this summer on
"Dream Team III."
</P>
<P>
The Dallas Morning Post story contradicts a report on Khtk
Radio in Sacramento Thursday that Richmond and Shawn Kemp of the
Seattle Supersonics were the two choices.
</P>
<P>
Barkley, who is averaging 23.6 points and 11.6 rebounds for
Phoenix, won the league's Most Valuable Player of the Year Award
in 1992-93. Barkley is one of just nine players in NBA history
with 20,000 points and 10,000 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
Richmond, who is averaging 23.3 points per game for Sacramento,
was the Most Valuable Player of the 1995 NBA All-Star Game and his
selection was supported by some of the league's most visible
performers, most notably Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Richmond is on pace to become just the seventh player in NBA
history to average 21 or more points per contest in each of his
first eight seasons.
</P>
<P>
Barkley was a member of Dream Team I that won the gold medal at
the 1992 Olympics in Barcelona. Richmond was a member of the 1988
Olympic team that won a bronze medal, the last U.S. Olympic team
comprised entirely of amateur players. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
