<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-12 23:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Follow Bonds Higher as Inflation Fears Retreat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Stocks on Wall Street gained
strength Friday with bond prices, as fresh economic data and lower
commodities prices eased fears of a resurgence of inflation.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average rose 45.52 points to 5,532.59,
recouping a fraction of the sell-off that occurred from Monday
through Wednesday. For the week, the Dow lost 150.29 points.
</P>
<P>
The closely watched indicator also is 157.15 points, or 2.8
percent, below the all-time closing high of 5,689.74, which was
set April 3.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts regarded the rebound as technical. But technical
or not, the advance was broad.
</P>
<P>
Gainers outnumbered losers by nearly 2 to 1. Volume was strong
at 411.95 million shares, but well below Thursday's 519.66 million
figure, the sixth-busiest day ever.
</P>
<P>
Broad market indexes followed the blue-chips higher. The NYSE's
composite index rose 3.03 to 342.41. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index rose 5.53 to 636.71. The Nasdaq composite index
rose 2.75 to 1,099.89, while the American Stock Exchange's market
value index rose 2.07 to 572.26.
</P>
<P>
Stocks got a big boost from the bond market, where the 30-year
Treasury bond yielding was 6.81 percent, down from 6.93 percent
late Thursday and an eight-month high of 6.94 percent Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Blue-chip stocks rose broadly. The Dow industrials were led
higher by stocks representing a diverse group of industries.
</P>
<P>
Interest-sensitive stocks, such as banking and finance
companies and utility shares, moved aggressively higher as
interest rates dropped in the bond market.
</P>
<P>
But computer-related stocks retreated, led by IBM.
</P>
<P>
Oil stocks fell as oil prices stumbled on heavy profit-taking.
May crude futures fell 1.94 U.S. dollars to 23.40 U.S. dollars a
barrel in New York. The price hit a five-year high of 25.34 U.S.
dollar a barrel on Thursday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
