<HEADLINE> Dollar Continues to Move Higher Against Mark, Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 12 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar rose Friday
against the German mark and Japanese yen on enhanced confidence in
the U.S. economy, ending a week of powerful gains for the
greenback.
</P>
<P>
In late New York trading, the dollar stood at 108.55 yen, up
from 108.41 yen Thursday and touched yet again a 26-month high
during the session. The dollar gained 0.8 percent against the yen
this week.
</P>
<P>
Against the mark, the dollar rose to 1.5035 marks from 1.5020
marks on Thursday. It gained 1.3 percent from last Friday's level.
</P>
<P>
Some traders expect the German central bank will reduce
interest rates. A cut in German rates would help the dollar
against the mark because relatively higher rates in the United
States would attract more funds.
</P>
<P>
The dollar's gains against the yen were more technically
driven, according to analysts.  
</P>
</TEXT>
