<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Prices Increase in UK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 12 (Xinhua) -- A sharp increase in UK house
prices has pushed the number of households in negative equity
below one million for the first time since 1992 and raised hopes
of a sustained housing market recovery.
</P>
<P>
House prices increased by a seasonally adjusted 1.2 percent in
March, after a one percent advance in February, according to the
Halifax Building Society, the UK's largest mortgage lender.
</P>
<P>
House prices increased in nine out of 12 UK regions. The
biggest gains were in Northern Ireland, Greater London and
southeast England.
</P>
<P>
UBS, the investment bank, estimated that the number of
households with mortgages higher than the value of their homes
declined by 22.7 percent to 964,000 in the first quarter, compared
with the last quarter of 1995. This is the largest decline in
three years.
</P>
<P>
Housebuilders and estate agents have reported a marked increase
in the level of housing market activity this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
