<HEADLINE> Mugabe Urges For Better Zimbabwe-Sino Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert
Mugabe said today that he hoped to further expand economic and
trade ties between Zimbabwe and China.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks here this afternoon in meeting with
visiting Chinese government agricultural delegation led by State
Councillor Chen Junsheng.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe highly praised the friendly relations between the two
peoples. He said, "Zimbabwe constantly regards China as a most
reliable friend."
</P>
<P>
On trade between the two countries, he hoped that China would
import more Zimbabwe's agricultural products and Zimbabwe would
import some necessities from China on the basis of mutual
benefit.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the point that there exist immense potential and
broad prospects in trade and economic cooperation between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Chen Junsheng conveyed the greetings from Chinese President
Jiang Zemin to President Robert Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
The state councillor also praised the Zimbabwean government to
implement the practical and flexible policy, making many
achievements in economic development in the country.
</P>
<P>
He urged the two countries to enhance the agricultural
cooperation. "The Zimbabwe's experience in production,
purchasing, processing and selling of tobacco and cotton merits
our learning," the Chinese state councillor said.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, Chen Junsheng called on Speaker of
Zimbabwean Parliament Cyril Ndebele.
</P>
<P>
The speaker told Chen Junsheng that the Zimbabwean parliament
is firm on its stand that "Taiwan is a inalienable part of the
Chinese territory."
</P>
<P>
Chen Junsheng expressed appreciation for the stand from the
Zimbabwean parliament.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese delegation arrived in Harare on April 10 for a
five-day visit to Zimbabwe. 
</P>
