<HEADLINE> Rawlings Flies To Liberia On Peace Mission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Ghanaian President Jerry Rawlings
flew to the Liberian Capital Monrovia today to appeal to rival
groups in that country to end their fighting, said a report
reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations, the West African peacekeeping force in
Liberia known as ECOMOG, and international diplomats have also
called on the rival factions to stop their armed clashes around
Monrovia.
</P>
<P>
Rawlings, who is currently the Chairman of the West African
Economic Community (ECOWAS), partly directs the ECOMOG peace-
keeping force. ECOWAS sent the peacekeepers to Liberia in August
1990, eight months after the Liberian civil war broke out.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG troops have not yet moved into the Mamba Point embassy
quarter of Monrovia, where up to 20,000 refugees are camped out
without access to food and water.
</P>
<P>
Eyewitnesses said that some people had already died because of
the bad conditions and doctors without borders said stopping
disease from spreading there was becoming impossible.
</P>
<P>
As thousands of heavily armed militia members have roamed the
capital for days, murdering people and plundering shops, tens of
thousands of local residents have been unable to gain access to
food and water.
</P>
<P>
Aid organizations have warned that the Liberian capital faced
mass starvation if the hostilities continued.
</P>
<P>
In the six years of the Liberian civil war, the capital has
been relatively safe until fighting erupted nearly a week ago
after the Liberian interim government tried to arrest Krahn tribe
militia warlord Roosevelt Johnson on murder charges. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
