<DATE_TIME> 1996-04-12 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Cars Take Top Place in Car Satisfaction  Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 12 (Xinhua) -- Japanese carmakers and their
dealers continue to deliver levels of customer satisfaction that
their British and other rivals "singularly fail to match",
according to the third annual survey of car satisfaction in the
UK.
</P>
<P>
The survey, which is regarded as the motorist's bible in
America, was carried out by J.D. Power and Associates, the U.S.
marketing information company and was based on responses from more
than 14,000 owners of L-registration (1993-94) cars in Britain.
</P>
<P>
Japanese vehicles took all top 10 places in the survey's
ranking of more than 70 cars on factors such as quality of
construction and reliability.
</P>
<P>
Only two European companies, Volkswagen's Skoda subsidiary and
BMW, made it into the top 10 list of companies with which
consumers felt most overall satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
The Toyota Corolla was the individual car scoring highest on
the satisfaction index, followed by the Honda Civic, Toyota Corona
and a variety of models from other Japanese carmakers including
Subaru and Daihatsu.
</P>
<P>
Britain's best-selling car, the Ford Escort, is third from the
bottom. Of the ten worst cars in the league table, six are
Vauxhalls and two Fords. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
